  "summary": "While searching for books, Hercule Poirot discusses the academic writing of Louis O'Malley and expresses his reverence for Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, specifically praising the character of Dr. Watson. He briefly mentions his friend Hastings, who is currently in South America.\n\nThe narrator, Colin Lamb, approaches Poirot to seek assistance with a murder case at 19 Wilbraham Crescent that lacks logical sense. Poirot listens to the details and describes the case as \"remarkable.\" While Lamb seeks an immediate solution, Poirot suggests that the case is likely simple despite its complicated appearance. Poirot experiences a sense of déjà vu, noting that the details follow a pattern similar to a previous case involving a soap-boiler in Liège, though he clarifies that the specific elements of the current case—such as the clocks, the fake insurance agent, and the blind woman—do not match that earlier instance.\n\nPoirot asserts that the police will eventually establish the identity of the deceased through scientific and investigative methods. He advises Lamb to return to the scene and \"chat\" with the neighbors rather than asking them directly if they saw anything suspicious, suggesting that clues are often hidden in casual conversation. Lamb reveals that he has already transcribed all neighbor conversations in shorthand. Finally, Poirot suggests that Lamb speak to the specific girl whom Lamb had previously held in his arms when she rushed out of the house in a panic.",
